WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.850 --> 00:00:04.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:23.570
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Peterson:
Good morning or afternoon.

00:00:23.570 --> 00:00:26.580
I'm not quite sure
which one it is, but --

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:29.040
My name is Betsy Peterson
and I'm the Director

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:32.080
of the American Folk Life Center
here at the Library of Congress,

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:36.090
and on behalf of all the staff
I want to welcome you here today

00:00:36.090 --> 00:00:42.860
for the latest in our Botkin,
Benjamin Botkin Lecture Series

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:46.650
which is an opportunity for
the American Folk Life Center

00:00:46.650 --> 00:00:52.890
to offer the very best and latest
in cultural heritage, oral history,

00:00:52.890 --> 00:00:55.270
ethnomusicology, and
folk life scholarship,

00:00:55.270 --> 00:00:58.310
and share that with all of you.

00:00:58.310 --> 00:01:02.540
The lecture series here allows
us to do a couple of things,

00:01:02.540 --> 00:01:06.610
not only share all of this great
information but each lecture

00:01:06.610 --> 00:01:12.030
that is given here is videotaped
and will eventually be webcast

00:01:12.030 --> 00:01:14.300 position:56%
so that researchers around the world

00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:18.670
and future researchers can
hear and learn from this.

00:01:18.670 --> 00:01:21.340
And it will become a
permanent part of our archive.

00:01:21.340 --> 00:01:25.230
So with that said, if you
could turn off any cell phones

00:01:25.230 --> 00:01:30.970
or any other electronic devices
I would greatly appreciate it.

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:33.440
Today we are really
thrilled to be able

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:37.620
to welcome a distinguished
colleague, Carol Silverman,

00:01:37.620 --> 00:01:41.940
who's an award-winning Professor of
Cultural Anthropology and Folklore

00:01:41.940 --> 00:01:45.760
at the University of
Oregon in Eugene.

00:01:45.760 --> 00:01:49.530
Dr. Silverman has been involved
with Balkan music and culture

00:01:49.530 --> 00:01:55.160
for over 30 years as a researcher,
teacher, activist, and performer.

00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:58.520
She has focused on Bulgaria
and Macedonia as well

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:03.370
as on Balkan Romani immigrants to
North American and Western Europe.

00:02:03.370 --> 00:02:08.160
Her work explores the relationship
among politics, ethnicity, ritual,

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:13.290
music, and gender as you can see
from the -- her most recent book,

00:02:13.290 --> 00:02:17.760
<i>Romani Roots Cultural Politics
and Balkan Music in Diaspora </i>,

00:02:17.760 --> 00:02:23.140
which is -- will be the topic
of the lecture here today.

00:02:23.140 --> 00:02:28.590
It was published in 2012
by Oxford University Press

00:02:28.590 --> 00:02:31.580
and it has won high
praise from all quarters,

00:02:31.580 --> 00:02:34.970
and received the prestigious
Allan Marion Book Prize

00:02:34.970 --> 00:02:38.290
from the Society for
Ethnomusicology.

00:02:38.290 --> 00:02:42.320
Over the years Carol Silverman's
research has been supported

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:47.530
by fellowships from the
Guggenheim Foundation, from NEH,

00:02:47.530 --> 00:02:51.550
ACLS or the American Council
for Learned Societies,

00:02:51.550 --> 00:02:54.090
and many other foundations.

00:02:54.090 --> 00:02:57.780
And in 2014 she was
inducted as a Fellow

00:02:57.780 --> 00:03:00.350
of the American Folklore Society.

00:03:00.350 --> 00:03:03.540
She is also a professional
performer in her own right.

00:03:03.540 --> 00:03:05.760
I know some of you may
have seen her yesterday.

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:12.660
She provided some introductions
for our concert of Esma Redzepova.

00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:17.690
But Carol also teachers Balkan
music and works with the NGO Voice

00:03:17.690 --> 00:03:21.640
of Roma based in California,
and I guess now

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:24.390
in Berlin, Germany as well.

00:03:24.390 --> 00:03:28.920
She has performed with numerous
musical groups including Zhenska

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:30.930
Pesna [phonetic] and Trio Slavej.

00:03:30.930 --> 00:03:34.650
And she's recorded with
the Yuri Yunakov Ensemble.

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:40.040
So, immediately following today's
talk we will have a short Question

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:44.180
and Answer period, and then
Dr. Silverman will be outside

00:03:44.180 --> 00:03:47.000
in the foyer and can sign books.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.140
But I want to encourage
you to go out there.

00:03:49.140 --> 00:03:53.040
Please buy one of the book
and talk with her some more.

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:57.510
So with that said, please join
me in welcoming Carol Silverman.

00:03:57.510 --> 00:04:02.810
[ Applause ]

00:04:02.810 --> 00:04:06.080
&gt;&gt; Carol Silverman: Thank you so
much Betsy Peterson, Nancy Groce,

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:08.250
Thea Austen, John Gold,
and all the staff

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:12.140
at the American Folklife
Center, for inviting me here.

00:04:12.140 --> 00:04:15.270 position:56%
Actually, I'm not really going to
talk about my book because I'm going

00:04:15.270 --> 00:04:19.690
to be talking about my newer
research that came out of the book.

00:04:19.690 --> 00:04:23.110
So whereas the book
focused more on Romani music

00:04:23.110 --> 00:04:25.490
in their own communities,
I'm actually talking

00:04:25.490 --> 00:04:30.640
about the popularization of
Romani music among non-Roma

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:34.460
and what happens when
appropriation arises,

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:39.180
what happens when the
management of Romani music is

00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:40.810
in the hands of non-Roma.

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:44.360
So you can see by my title
I've put "Gypsy" for a --

00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:46.120
in quotes very prominently.

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:50.400
And that's because I only use it,
actually, as a marketing term.

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:54.900
Roma use the word "Gypsy" --
Roma do not use the word "Gypsy"

00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:57.920 position:56%
if there are Romani speaking when
they're speaking their own language.

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:01.280
And so I'll be talking about
names a little bit later.

00:05:01.280 --> 00:05:05.280
"Gypsy" is an outsider term,
sometimes used by insiders,

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:07.960
but Romani-speaking Roma
would prefer the word "Roma."

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:10.000 position:56%
It means a person in their language.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.590
And in the English language
"Gypsy" is an ethnic slur.

00:05:13.590 --> 00:05:18.950
It means to swindle or to cheat
somebody, like he gypped me.

00:05:18.950 --> 00:05:20.250
So I avoid that term.

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:24.250
But I can't when I'm studying the
marketing of music because it's

00:05:24.250 --> 00:05:26.180
under the rubric "Gypsy" music.

00:05:26.180 --> 00:05:27.530
So remember the quotes.

00:05:27.530 --> 00:05:32.460
So today I'm going to be talking
about the pathways of Romani music

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:39.130
into commercial markets, DJs,
celebrities, production houses

00:05:39.130 --> 00:05:41.030
around the world, festivals.

00:05:41.030 --> 00:05:46.580 position:56%
For example, this festival that I
studied in Belgium that continues --

00:05:46.580 --> 00:05:49.960
actually, it's happening right
now, the Balkan Traffic Festival,

00:05:49.960 --> 00:05:55.200 position:56%
that actually under the rubric
"Balkan" has about 90% Romani music.

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:58.850
So these days the word "Balkan"
and "Gypsy" are starting

00:05:58.850 --> 00:06:03.250
to mean the same thing even
though Romani music has many,

00:06:03.250 --> 00:06:06.240
many genres that are in
Balkan and many regions,

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:09.700
and Balkan music has many
genres that aren't Romani.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:17.660 position:56%
So there's a collapsing then of sort
of the market into a singular path.

00:06:17.660 --> 00:06:21.230
This festival featured
three Balkan brass bands,

00:06:21.230 --> 00:06:23.780
and that's another
collapsing at this moment

00:06:23.780 --> 00:06:28.060
because the most popular
Balkan Roman music genre

00:06:28.060 --> 00:06:30.820
in popularity is brass
music which is, again,

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:34.840
a tiny part of Balkan Romani
music in its entirety.

00:06:34.840 --> 00:06:37.170
But for outside audiences it seems

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:40.400
like all Roma are doing
is playing brass music.

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:46.790
So the man in the white hat is
Marko Markovich from the Boban

00:06:46.790 --> 00:06:50.230
and Marko Markovich Brass
Band in Southern Serbia.

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:55.260
But the first person listed there
is Goran Bregovic, I'll be talking

00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:59.980
about him later, as a
non-Romani appropriator of music

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:04.100
who made Balkan music
popular in his film scores.

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:07.760
So we'll be looking at films,
we'll be looing at festivals.

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:10.440
I'm giving you a little
taste of what's to come

00:07:10.440 --> 00:07:12.040
in the first five minutes.

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:16.000
So where do we find
quote Gypsies these days?

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.330
We find Gypsies in the New York
Gypsy Festival which is now,

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:21.980
I think, in its 11th year.

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:26.880 position:56%
And every year the Statue of Liberty
plays a different Romani instrument.

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:31.880
But this festival over the years
has had fewer and fewer Roma,

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:34.480
so this is a trend
I'll be talking about,

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:37.700
"Gypsy" music without Roma, okay?

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:40.370
So if you have their music, and
other people are playing it,

00:07:40.370 --> 00:07:44.740 position:56%
and people don't know much about it,
why do you really need Roma anyway?

00:07:44.740 --> 00:07:49.530
Another group, Gogol Bordello,
who coined the term "Gypsy Punk"

00:07:49.530 --> 00:07:55.390
as a genre, headed by the
former DJ Eugene Hutz,

00:07:55.390 --> 00:07:58.500
they became really famous and
they've crossed over not only

00:07:58.500 --> 00:08:03.210
to world music audiences
but to pop music audiences.

00:08:03.210 --> 00:08:05.890
So they perform at
festivals like Coachella

00:08:05.890 --> 00:08:08.710 position:56%
and the biggest festivals in Europe.

00:08:08.710 --> 00:08:11.600
And they're no longer
even world music.

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:16.400
When they started out, Eugene Hutz
claimed he was one-fourth Romani

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:17.700
from Ukraine.

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:22.580
People in the New York Community
of Roma said "not really, no."

00:08:22.580 --> 00:08:25.950
But as he got more famous everyone
sort of has to agree with him

00:08:25.950 --> 00:08:27.950
because he's the guy with the gigs.

00:08:27.950 --> 00:08:29.680
He's the one who has the contracts.

00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:31.270
Everyone wants to work with him.

00:08:31.270 --> 00:08:35.760 position:56%
So now many more members of his band
are even claiming that they're Roma.

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:38.130
So one of the paradoxes
I'm talking about is

00:08:38.130 --> 00:08:43.240
that in the music scene it's a
cache, it's a step up, to be Roma.

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:47.990
But outside the music scene it's
absolutely low-class status.

00:08:47.990 --> 00:08:51.570
And this is the paradox
that Roma are admired

00:08:51.570 --> 00:08:53.830
for their music but
reviled as people.

00:08:53.830 --> 00:08:57.490
So I'll be introducing the
political situation of the music.

00:08:57.490 --> 00:09:01.940
Madonna also got involved in
Romani music in her Sticky

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:05.330
and Sweet Tour in 2008/2009.

00:09:05.330 --> 00:09:09.330
She actually invited Eugene
Hutz to perform with her,

00:09:09.330 --> 00:09:11.990
the guy from Gogol
Bordello, but he was too busy.

00:09:11.990 --> 00:09:17.200
And we lobbied Eugene to
substitute other people for him

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:20.350
because other Roma should
get a break in their career.

00:09:20.350 --> 00:09:24.460
And, finally, Madonna agreed
to invite the Kolpakov Trio,

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:26.530
which actually includes
one Jewish member.

00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:31.740
The violinist Arkady Gips is from
Ukraine, living in Columbus, Ohio.

00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:35.300
He's played Romani music quite
a lot, and the Roma wanted him.

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:39.270
So on Madonna's tour you
had a 75-year-old guitarist,

00:09:39.270 --> 00:09:42.660
the uncle of the young guitarist.

00:09:42.660 --> 00:09:44.580
And this is unusual for Madonna.

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:46.870
But did she do anything
for Romani music?

00:09:46.870 --> 00:09:48.850
Well, people heard the music.

00:09:48.850 --> 00:09:51.690
She did in Bucharest, Romania.

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:55.080
She put down her guitar
and asked for quiet.

00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:59.040
And she asked the audience,
"Do you love gypsy music?"

00:09:59.040 --> 00:10:00.340
"Yeah, we love Gypsy music."

00:10:00.340 --> 00:10:03.060 position:56%
"I'm so happy you love gypsy music."

00:10:03.060 --> 00:10:07.170
And then she said, "But I'm so
upset that you don't like Gypsies."

00:10:07.170 --> 00:10:10.520
And then she was booed
by 60,000 people

00:10:10.520 --> 00:10:12.800
in the stadium she
was performing in.

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:16.510
And the international
headlines were,

00:10:16.510 --> 00:10:20.790 position:56%
"Madonna doesn't understand
anything about our gypsy situation."

00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:22.090
What did she do?

00:10:22.090 --> 00:10:23.390
Well, she was lobbied

00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:25.260
by the musicians backstage
to say something.

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:27.740
So she tried, but failed.

00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:32.450
And then post-concert, she
sold one shoe at an auction

00:10:32.450 --> 00:10:34.860
and donated it for a Romani cause.

00:10:34.860 --> 00:10:37.140
So that's the sum total of Madonna.

00:10:37.140 --> 00:10:41.160
But she's very important because
she actually included the music.

00:10:41.160 --> 00:10:43.590
And then, of course, we have Borat.

00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:46.020
If you remember that film where 95%

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:48.880
of the music was Balkan
Romani music,

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:55.290
and the film itself was staged in
Glod, Romania, in southern Romania,

00:10:55.290 --> 00:10:59.440 position:56%
a Romani village where the villagers
themselves did sign releases

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:04.680
for $10 a day because they knew
this was a good income for them.

00:11:04.680 --> 00:11:08.830
But they had no idea they would
be pictured as Kazakhstanis

00:11:08.830 --> 00:11:13.340
in bestiality positions,
incest-type scenes.

00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:19.100 position:56%
And they actually tried to sue Sasha
Cohen as well as many other people

00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:21.680
in this film tried to sue him.

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:25.190
But nobody actually can
win against Sasha Cohen

00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:28.420
and his Hollywood legal team.

00:11:28.420 --> 00:11:32.530
Another woman who was featured
in that film, Esma Redzepova,

00:11:32.530 --> 00:11:34.600
and she's performing tonight.

00:11:34.600 --> 00:11:39.230
If you are all free you
will not be disappointed.

00:11:39.230 --> 00:11:42.550
This is a legend of Romani
music from Macedonia,

00:11:42.550 --> 00:11:46.460
and she will be performing at the
Millennium Stage at 6 p.m. tonight.

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:50.090
She also sued Sasha
Cohen because her --

00:11:50.090 --> 00:11:56.000
the song that was used in the
film was on a Dutch label,

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.170
but she had a clause, she's very
smart, unlike a lot of other Roma

00:12:00.170 --> 00:12:04.370
who actually don't have the legal
background to put these clauses

00:12:04.370 --> 00:12:07.490
in their contracts, or they
don't have contracts at all.

00:12:07.490 --> 00:12:11.000
She had a legal clause in her
contract with the Dutch firm

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.810
that said if it's used, her
music is used in a film,

00:12:13.810 --> 00:12:16.120 position:56%
she had to give personal permission.

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:17.420
And they did not.

00:12:17.420 --> 00:12:18.720
The film just gave it.

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:20.410
So she was able to
recover some money

00:12:20.410 --> 00:12:23.990
from the Dutch film,
not from Sasha Cohen.

00:12:23.990 --> 00:12:28.150
And another recent thing is
Jason Derulo's hit "Talk Dirty,"

00:12:28.150 --> 00:12:33.430
which used a saxophone riff,
which many Balkan Roma listened

00:12:33.430 --> 00:12:34.730
to and said, "Oh, my god.

00:12:34.730 --> 00:12:38.330 position:56%
That sounds like Udi Yunakov or some
of our famous saxophone players."

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:41.460
It was definitely a
Balkan saxophone riff.

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:45.620
But, actually, it was taken from
Balkan Beat Box, a group composed

00:12:45.620 --> 00:12:48.300
of Americans and Israelis, no Roma.

00:12:48.300 --> 00:12:50.540
But the saxophone player,
Ori Kaplan,

00:12:50.540 --> 00:12:53.330
in the group took lessons
from Udi Yunakov.

00:12:53.330 --> 00:12:56.280
Actually, he's one of the
National Heritage Fellows

00:12:56.280 --> 00:12:59.700
and you've seen him
here in Washington.

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:03.500
Udi lives in New Jersey, and
Ori took lessons for him.

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:07.510
But Ori took his music,
put it on this album,

00:13:07.510 --> 00:13:10.390
and then when Jason Derulo
needed to license it,

00:13:10.390 --> 00:13:12.170
it didn't involve Uri at all.

00:13:12.170 --> 00:13:15.900
So there's Uri's music
but without Uri anymore.

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:17.940
And where else are
Gypsies these days?

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:21.090
Well, we can see Gypsies on
television in reality shows.

00:13:21.090 --> 00:13:24.430
If you know the history
of this particular show,

00:13:24.430 --> 00:13:28.300
it started in England as
<i>My Big Fat Gypsy Wedding </i>.

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:32.720
It got the largest viewership
of the BBC channel it was on.

00:13:32.720 --> 00:13:38.760 position:56%
It's a sensational show, emphasizing
violence, sexuality, teen marriages,

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:43.750
conflict in the society, and
it isn't even about Gypsies.

00:13:43.750 --> 00:13:48.880
It's about Travelers or people who
have intermarried in England, Roma,

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:52.160
and Travelers, and even
groups that were paid

00:13:52.160 --> 00:13:55.750
to stage these exotic-type rituals.

00:13:55.750 --> 00:13:57.490
And so we have, basically --

00:13:57.490 --> 00:14:01.700
this is the information that
the public knows about Roma.

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:04.010
And then the TLC took
it up in America

00:14:04.010 --> 00:14:07.660
and made the American version
using families from the south

00:14:07.660 --> 00:14:09.300
in Texas and Mississippi.

00:14:09.300 --> 00:14:10.790
They, again, were paid

00:14:10.790 --> 00:14:14.420
to do exaggerated type
of rituals and violence.

00:14:14.420 --> 00:14:18.320
Then the National Geographic
Channel took up this kind

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:21.300
of craze for Gypsy reality TV.

00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:23.490
We thought maybe it would
be more educational.

00:14:23.490 --> 00:14:26.700
They even tried to
appear educational

00:14:26.700 --> 00:14:29.890
by putting a Romani
glossary on their website.

00:14:29.890 --> 00:14:32.250
And they asked scholars
for endorsements.

00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:35.540
Of course we were very,
very, very suspicious.

00:14:35.540 --> 00:14:37.590
I'm not Romani myself,
but I work with Roma

00:14:37.590 --> 00:14:40.420
and basically people
ask you for endorsements

00:14:40.420 --> 00:14:42.300
of Gypsy projects all the time,

00:14:42.300 --> 00:14:44.080
and you have to be
really, really careful.

00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:47.440
So you can tell this is, again,

00:14:47.440 --> 00:14:50.720
sensational about fortunetelling
scams.

00:14:50.720 --> 00:14:53.310
This is about the Kalderash
Group, a family in New York.

00:14:53.310 --> 00:14:56.250
But, again, they were paid
to exaggerate their customs,

00:14:56.250 --> 00:14:59.320
to fight on camera on purpose.

00:14:59.320 --> 00:15:05.240
Okay. So, in addition, there's an
entire network of DJs doing sampled

00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:11.620
and digitized Roma music which
they take from Balkan groups

00:15:11.620 --> 00:15:13.380
and they have trademarked the name.

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:16.270
It is a, under trademark,
BalkanBeats.

00:15:16.270 --> 00:15:18.610
And this is a whole
network of hundreds of DJs.

00:15:18.610 --> 00:15:23.140
They started in Western Europe
and now they've gone to America

00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:26.480
and Japan, Australia, and Mexico.

00:15:26.480 --> 00:15:27.780
It's very big.

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:29.330
So I'll be talking about
this scene as well,

00:15:29.330 --> 00:15:31.660
the kind of sampled
world of Balkan music.

00:15:31.660 --> 00:15:35.360
And then here in New York
we have many different clubs

00:15:35.360 --> 00:15:37.140
that have this kind of music,

00:15:37.140 --> 00:15:40.420
sometimes mixed with
live Romani music.

00:15:40.420 --> 00:15:44.170
But a lot of sampled music where
you don't need Roma anymore.

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:47.890
So just to review, basically,
I am talking about this paradox

00:15:47.890 --> 00:15:52.620
that Roma are revered for their
music, yet reviled as people.

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:57.080
And historically the stereotype
about Gypsies is two-pronged.

00:15:57.080 --> 00:16:02.220
One may appear to be positive
because it's about romanticism,

00:16:02.220 --> 00:16:05.770
musicality, talented people
who don't need to work,

00:16:05.770 --> 00:16:10.890
who sit around the fire
every day enjoying music.

00:16:10.890 --> 00:16:16.070
It's a stereotype that is totally
fantasy and it goes hand-in-hand

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:18.380
with the negative stereotype
of criminality

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:21.830
and don't trust these people
and they will steal from you.

00:16:21.830 --> 00:16:23.820 position:56%
So I would say even, and, of course,

00:16:23.820 --> 00:16:26.110
stereotypes have been
studied by scholars.

00:16:26.110 --> 00:16:29.720
We know that the positive and
the negative are intertwined.

00:16:29.720 --> 00:16:31.650
This is very true for
African Americans.

00:16:31.650 --> 00:16:33.900
Not everybody is a
basketball player.

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:37.390
Very, very important to look
at positive stereotyping

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:39.250
and the damage that it does.

00:16:39.250 --> 00:16:42.570
And I don't even call it positive,
but in the literature you call it.

00:16:42.570 --> 00:16:44.670
And I mentioned already
the name issue

00:16:44.670 --> 00:16:48.590 position:56%
that I'm not using Gypsy except when
I have to for the marketing label,

00:16:48.590 --> 00:16:50.450
and that's actually
what I'm studying.

00:16:50.450 --> 00:16:53.910
The other labels, Tsigan,
which is tsigganos, Tsigane,

00:16:53.910 --> 00:16:56.820
in many different European
languages, those --

00:16:56.820 --> 00:17:01.720
that's also a false label because
it comes from the word "Athinganoi"

00:17:01.720 --> 00:17:05.020
which is from a Byzantine
heretical sect,

00:17:05.020 --> 00:17:07.780
and those were not
related to Roma either.

00:17:07.780 --> 00:17:11.430
That word is also a
putdown in many, many Balkan

00:17:11.430 --> 00:17:15.750
and Slavic romance languages.

00:17:15.750 --> 00:17:20.430
Okay. So what are we talking about
-- just a little bit of history?

00:17:20.430 --> 00:17:26.220
We're talking about Roma as an
Indian diaspora from South Asia.

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:32.070 position:56%
Linguistic evidence has led us to
tie the Romani language to Sanskrit,

00:17:32.070 --> 00:17:35.160
and even to modern-day
Hindi, and the diversity

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:39.320
of Romani subgroups even in
earlier migration, but definitely

00:17:39.320 --> 00:17:41.460
in the current-day diaspora.

00:17:41.460 --> 00:17:45.280
Okay? So some people ask
what does unite Roma?

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:48.140
Well, if they speak the Romani
language they can understand

00:17:48.140 --> 00:17:49.440
each other.

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:52.490
But only half the world's Roma
speak Romani because it wasn't

00:17:52.490 --> 00:17:56.000
to their advantage in some places
to continue their language.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.590
Some Roma passed out
of that category.

00:17:58.590 --> 00:18:02.110
Some were forced by
governments, schools,

00:18:02.110 --> 00:18:04.850
to abandon their language,
to leave it.

00:18:04.850 --> 00:18:10.020
Okay? So even nomadism and
sedentarism is a complicated issue.

00:18:10.020 --> 00:18:12.740
Not all Roma are nomadic,
and even those

00:18:12.740 --> 00:18:17.920
that are nomadic might have
been forced to move due to wars,

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:20.520
due to evictions, due to prejudice.

00:18:20.520 --> 00:18:23.720 position:56%
So there are Roma, for example, in
the Balkans that have been sedentary

00:18:23.720 --> 00:18:28.470
for hundreds of years and
don't relate well to nomadism.

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:32.120
Or they might be seasonal
nomads or musical nomads

00:18:32.120 --> 00:18:34.390
because they find their craft.

00:18:34.390 --> 00:18:39.400
Metal craft workers perhaps
would take a seasonal route in --

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:41.330
certainly we have evidence of Roma

00:18:41.330 --> 00:18:45.580
in the Middle Ages taking their
forges, their blacksmithing tools,

00:18:45.580 --> 00:18:48.480 position:56%
from town to town to service people.

00:18:48.480 --> 00:18:52.090
So Roma have been very integrated
into the economy of Europe

00:18:52.090 --> 00:18:56.820
for hundreds of years as
metalworkers, horse doctors,

00:18:56.820 --> 00:19:00.640
musicians, middlemen,
peddlers, some fortunetellers --

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:05.540
although not all groups --
offering amulets or advice.

00:19:05.540 --> 00:19:10.650 position:56%
You might say it's a folk psychiatry
before psychiatry was invented.

00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:12.900
Some of the very tragic periods

00:19:12.900 --> 00:19:16.350
of Romani history need
to be mentioned here.

00:19:16.350 --> 00:19:20.870
Slavery in Southern Romania,
in Wallachia and Moldavia,

00:19:20.870 --> 00:19:25.810
for 500 years where Roma were owned
by the church and by the nobility,

00:19:25.810 --> 00:19:29.560
and traded at auctions,
selected and sorted according

00:19:29.560 --> 00:19:32.720
to their populations
and their occupations --

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:35.150
the gold washers, the
agricultural workers,

00:19:35.150 --> 00:19:37.220
the musicians, the horse dealers.

00:19:37.220 --> 00:19:42.870
The Nazi period in which Roma
were singled out for extinction

00:19:42.870 --> 00:19:45.170
and genocide just like Jews.

00:19:45.170 --> 00:19:47.730
And now we know over a million --

00:19:47.730 --> 00:19:51.230
well, half-a-million to
a million Roma perished.

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:55.700
And a lot of activism about
getting the recognition

00:19:55.700 --> 00:19:58.020
of Roma in the Holocaust.

00:19:58.020 --> 00:20:01.720
Our Holocaust Museum here in
America, when it first opened here

00:20:01.720 --> 00:20:05.640
on the Mall, had a
Romani Board Member,

00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:08.120
and then when that
person stepped down,

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:12.350
for over 10 years there was
no Romani person on the Board.

00:20:12.350 --> 00:20:18.840
Just this year, Ethel Brooks from
Rutgers University was appointed.

00:20:18.840 --> 00:20:22.560
So it's a constant battle
to get recognition of Roma.

00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:27.100
Many other things during the
more recent Socialist period

00:20:27.100 --> 00:20:32.130
such as taking the wheels off
of caravans of nomadic Roma,

00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:36.020
making their music illegal,
banning their language,

00:20:36.020 --> 00:20:39.380
banning Romani types of dress.

00:20:39.380 --> 00:20:41.720
Many, many things can be listed.

00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:46.790 position:56%
Probably most striking would be the
forced sterilization or Romani women

00:20:46.790 --> 00:20:54.300 position:56%
in Hungary, Czechoslovakia,
Finland, Sweden, places in the West,

00:20:54.300 --> 00:20:57.140
just like other indigenous
groups, the Sami,

00:20:57.140 --> 00:21:00.090
and this has happened
certainly in America as well.

00:21:00.090 --> 00:21:02.110 position:56%
And still today we have the tracking

00:21:02.110 --> 00:21:04.750
of Romani children
into special schools.

00:21:04.750 --> 00:21:07.180
This means, assuming
that they are disabled

00:21:07.180 --> 00:21:10.670
because perhaps they speak the
majority language with an accent

00:21:10.670 --> 00:21:14.770 position:56%
or just their dark skin, and putting
them into schools for the disabled

00:21:14.770 --> 00:21:16.930
which is a track you
never get out of,

00:21:16.930 --> 00:21:19.660 position:56%
and you're not in an academic track.

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:25.200
And a very important case was
adjudicated in the town of Ostrava

00:21:25.200 --> 00:21:27.480
in the Czech Republic
where they showed

00:21:27.480 --> 00:21:32.330
that it was 27 times more
likely for a Romani child to end

00:21:32.330 --> 00:21:35.550
up in a special school
than a Czech student.

00:21:35.550 --> 00:21:38.290
And still, in the European
Court of Human Rights

00:21:38.290 --> 00:21:41.020
that case failed the first time.

00:21:41.020 --> 00:21:42.320
It only won on appeal.

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:46.980
So these are the kinds of battles
that Roma and allies are fighting.

00:21:46.980 --> 00:21:49.180
And if you think the U.S.
is a little more open,

00:21:49.180 --> 00:21:53.270
it is in some ways, just because
Americans are more private.

00:21:53.270 --> 00:21:57.400
But still in the U.S., in
southern states there are quote

00:21:57.400 --> 00:22:01.350
"gypsy crime units" attached
to police departments.

00:22:01.350 --> 00:22:06.680 position:56%
They're called Bunco Squads and they
are paid for by your tax dollars

00:22:06.680 --> 00:22:11.330
and they assume that there are Roma
who do certain kinds of crimes,

00:22:11.330 --> 00:22:15.190 position:56%
and only those crimes are done by
Roma, and only Roma do those crimes.

00:22:15.190 --> 00:22:20.310
So it's a real huge assumption and
it's a form of racial profiling.

00:22:20.310 --> 00:22:23.730
And not to mention what I'd
call the entire erasure of Roma

00:22:23.730 --> 00:22:26.790
from European history,
American history, and so on.

00:22:26.790 --> 00:22:30.330
So today Roma is the
largest minority in Europe.

00:22:30.330 --> 00:22:33.850
The majority actually
reside in EU states.

00:22:33.850 --> 00:22:37.080
And they have some of the lowest
rates of social integration,

00:22:37.080 --> 00:22:40.020
you can see here on the
PowerPoint, in healthcare,

00:22:40.020 --> 00:22:42.240
education, all of the indicators.

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:44.740
But most striking, of
course, is employment,

00:22:44.740 --> 00:22:48.340
how little employment there
are because of discrimination

00:22:48.340 --> 00:22:52.390
and also Roma were
tracked out of skilled jobs

00:22:52.390 --> 00:22:54.130
in the Socialist government.

00:22:54.130 --> 00:22:56.100 position:56%
All the streetcleaners, for example,

00:22:56.100 --> 00:22:59.850
were Roma in Poland,
Bulgaria, Romania.

00:22:59.850 --> 00:23:02.710
So after socialism, many
didn't have the skills.

00:23:02.710 --> 00:23:06.550
And those that had the skills
were not allowed to assume jobs.

00:23:06.550 --> 00:23:08.150
They're just cut out.

00:23:08.150 --> 00:23:13.010
And there's tremendous prejudice
against Roma in Europe today.

00:23:13.010 --> 00:23:16.450
When I do my field work, even
educated professors tell me, "Oh,

00:23:16.450 --> 00:23:18.380
don't go to that Romani
neighborhood.

00:23:18.380 --> 00:23:20.580
You'll be killed, you'll be raped."

00:23:20.580 --> 00:23:22.730
Of course, they've never been
in that Romani neighborhood.

00:23:22.730 --> 00:23:26.170
They don't know any Roma, but
they have the historic prejudices.

00:23:26.170 --> 00:23:28.340
And then if I invite them,
they'll say, "Oh, my God.

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:30.430
This is an amazingly nice house.

00:23:30.430 --> 00:23:32.210
I had no idea."

00:23:32.210 --> 00:23:34.710
You know, contact really does help.

00:23:34.710 --> 00:23:36.210
And the most upsetting
thing, of course,

00:23:36.210 --> 00:23:39.250
is physical violence
and intimidation.

00:23:39.250 --> 00:23:43.710
Lots of incidences of targeting
of Roma, burning down houses.

00:23:43.710 --> 00:23:45.930
Many of these cases are
still in the courts.

00:23:45.930 --> 00:23:48.390
Roma rarely get justice.

00:23:48.390 --> 00:23:51.970
This has been compounded
these days by migration.

00:23:51.970 --> 00:23:59.010 position:56%
So after the wall came down in 1989,
many Roma, of course, wanted to move

00:23:59.010 --> 00:24:02.150
to Western Europe for better
jobs, better opportunities.

00:24:02.150 --> 00:24:04.960
And it turns out West Europeans
are pretty prejudiced, too.

00:24:04.960 --> 00:24:09.120
So there's been a hysteria,
a panic, about the floods,

00:24:09.120 --> 00:24:11.550
the migrations, of East Europeans.

00:24:11.550 --> 00:24:15.110
You might know the Italian
fingerprinting incident a few years

00:24:15.110 --> 00:24:17.380
ago where the Italian government --

00:24:17.380 --> 00:24:21.280
Berlusconi decided to
fingerprint all Roma,

00:24:21.280 --> 00:24:23.620
to have a database for criminality.

00:24:23.620 --> 00:24:26.460
This is so reminiscent
of World War II.

00:24:26.460 --> 00:24:29.530
Okay? Can you imagine that,
an entire ethnic group?

00:24:29.530 --> 00:24:33.800 position:56%
There have been expulsions of EU
citizens, who have the right to work

00:24:33.800 --> 00:24:36.700
in Western Europe,
back to Eastern Europe.

00:24:36.700 --> 00:24:41.600
And outside the EU, in places like
Kosovo where it is really not safe

00:24:41.600 --> 00:24:45.670
for Roma to be there, there
are expulsions back to Kosovo

00:24:45.670 --> 00:24:50.350
of children, families who have
raised an entire generation

00:24:50.350 --> 00:24:51.970
in Western Europe.

00:24:51.970 --> 00:24:56.600
There are continuing
demonstrations against Roma.

00:24:56.600 --> 00:24:59.900
It's a very tense situation.

00:24:59.900 --> 00:25:03.340
And you might remember the
Greek "Blond Maria" incident

00:25:03.340 --> 00:25:10.000 position:56%
where a blond six-year-old was found
in a Turkish Romani settlement.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:13.530
Pardon me, a Greek
Romani settlement.

00:25:13.530 --> 00:25:16.790
And the -- when the police
saw her they assumed,

00:25:16.790 --> 00:25:19.340
because she's blond,
that she was kidnapped.

00:25:19.340 --> 00:25:24.380
So this is a really old
European stereotype,

00:25:24.380 --> 00:25:27.260
you know, stolen by the Gypsies.

00:25:27.260 --> 00:25:30.260 position:56%
And actually when they
investigated -- it took a long time,

00:25:30.260 --> 00:25:34.290
and all the media was about
the "abducted Maria," okay,

00:25:34.290 --> 00:25:36.560
"blond Maria abduction" narrative.

00:25:36.560 --> 00:25:39.010
When they found out what happened,

00:25:39.010 --> 00:25:42.930
it was actually a Bulgarian
Romani family who was albino

00:25:42.930 --> 00:25:46.490
who was working for
better wages in Greece

00:25:46.490 --> 00:25:51.310
and the Greek Romani family offered
to watch the kids and raise them

00:25:51.310 --> 00:25:53.590
because it's a better standard,
even though it looked pretty bad

00:25:53.590 --> 00:25:55.980
to the police when they
saw the "blond Maria."

00:25:55.980 --> 00:25:58.490
The Bulgarian family had
worse standard of living

00:25:58.490 --> 00:26:01.530
and left their child
there voluntarily,

00:26:01.530 --> 00:26:05.090
to be raised by a higher
class Romani family.

00:26:05.090 --> 00:26:08.730
But the ramifications of
this incident were terrible.

00:26:08.730 --> 00:26:13.480 position:56%
Even as far as England, Roma, Romani
chilcren in England were going

00:26:13.480 --> 00:26:16.750
to school and being told,
"Oh, well, you know,

00:26:16.750 --> 00:26:19.960
do you have a blond
sister in your basement?"

00:26:19.960 --> 00:26:22.210
You know, "Did you
steal my blond sister?"

00:26:22.210 --> 00:26:24.580
Terrible types of ramifications.

00:26:24.580 --> 00:26:28.380
So here's some photos of some
of the things that are going on.

00:26:28.380 --> 00:26:32.450 position:56%
The Hungarian Guard, which was
actually banned, is an informal part

00:26:32.450 --> 00:26:36.030
of the Jobbik Party which sits
in the Hungarian Parliament,

00:26:36.030 --> 00:26:42.370
a xenophobic party that patrols
villages to keep Gypsies out.

00:26:42.370 --> 00:26:47.090
And they are using Nazi
symbolism and it is quite scary.

00:26:47.090 --> 00:26:50.120
And there have been
anti-Romani protests everywhere.

00:26:50.120 --> 00:26:53.350
This happens to be
one from Bulgaria.

00:26:53.350 --> 00:26:55.120
So now back to music.

00:26:55.120 --> 00:26:57.000
What does music have
to do with politics?

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:01.130
Well, music never operates
outside of the political sphere.

00:27:01.130 --> 00:27:04.950
It is actually one of the realms
where Roma have some control.

00:27:04.950 --> 00:27:08.870
But what I'm going to show is that
this control is being contested

00:27:08.870 --> 00:27:13.580
in the commercial markets by
a lot of non-Romani forces.

00:27:13.580 --> 00:27:16.330
So I wanted to show you a
little bit about the music

00:27:16.330 --> 00:27:19.030
in some traditional
Romani communities --

00:27:19.030 --> 00:27:22.980
that kind of music that you won't
see on the commercial stage, okay?

00:27:22.980 --> 00:27:24.280
So I'm going to be looking

00:27:24.280 --> 00:27:27.100
at insider/outsider
boundaries and so on.

00:27:27.100 --> 00:27:33.290
So here are some Romani settlements
in -- this one is in Bulgaria,

00:27:33.290 --> 00:27:36.760
in a Western Thrace, and
this is a wedding from 1990.

00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:41.300
And this is another wedding from
1984, in Western Thrace as well.

00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:44.710
Roma communities coalesce
around music.

00:27:44.710 --> 00:27:48.350
It is a very important
performative means

00:27:48.350 --> 00:27:52.840
to show your family solidarity,
your extended kin networks,

00:27:52.840 --> 00:27:57.850
how you are allied, and, of course,
the artistry of the music itself.

00:27:57.850 --> 00:28:00.580
Plus gender roles are
extremely important.

00:28:00.580 --> 00:28:03.080
Women are very much
in charge of rituals.

00:28:03.080 --> 00:28:06.470
They have knowledge that they
impart to the younger generation,

00:28:06.470 --> 00:28:08.200
to tell them what to do when.

00:28:08.200 --> 00:28:13.450
These women are bringing gifts in
Macedonia to the bride's family,

00:28:13.450 --> 00:28:17.110
and those gifts will
actually be opened one by one,

00:28:17.110 --> 00:28:20.470
and in public people will
announce who they came from,

00:28:20.470 --> 00:28:23.840
how much they cost, and
where this person is located.

00:28:23.840 --> 00:28:27.860
So this diaspora of family
security is very important.

00:28:27.860 --> 00:28:30.510
So let's look at a few
videos of these very short.

00:28:30.510 --> 00:28:34.180
[ Film: Singing and
sounds from the crowd ]

00:28:34.180 --> 00:28:39.080
So we are in Macedonia,
in Suto Orizaro,

00:28:39.080 --> 00:28:42.100
one of the largest Romani
neighborhoods outside

00:28:42.100 --> 00:28:44.490
of Skopje known as Sutka.

00:28:44.490 --> 00:28:50.880
And these are the groomswomen
in a wedding bringing gifts

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:54.470
to the bride's family
with zurla-tapan

00:28:54.470 --> 00:28:57.740
which is a historic
Romani instrument.

00:28:57.740 --> 00:29:02.370
In fact, it's been a monopoly of
Roma for 500 years until recently,

00:29:02.370 --> 00:29:04.420
when non-Roma are learning it.

00:29:04.420 --> 00:29:07.510
And it's an outdoor
procession type of instrument.

00:29:07.510 --> 00:29:10.870
[ Music ]

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:13.930
This is the henna party
for the bride.

00:29:13.930 --> 00:29:20.510
You could see henna on a round
tray with red gauze on top of it.

00:29:20.510 --> 00:29:25.520
[ Music ]

00:29:25.520 --> 00:29:26.820
Okay. So let me go on.

00:29:26.820 --> 00:29:28.120
Just going to give
you a little taste.

00:29:28.120 --> 00:29:30.190 position:56%
So, back to my argument about music.

00:29:30.190 --> 00:29:34.730
This is one type of very historic
and contemporary Romani music

00:29:34.730 --> 00:29:38.090
that you will not find
at any Western festivals,

00:29:38.090 --> 00:29:40.300
or even on CDs readily available.

00:29:40.300 --> 00:29:44.440
But it is very much a
part of Balkan Roma life.

00:29:44.440 --> 00:29:47.440
Here's another wedding
in Sutka, Macedonia.

00:29:47.440 --> 00:29:53.680
And now we'll look at
some dancing on the day

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:57.020
of the henna party for the bride.

00:29:57.020 --> 00:29:58.630
These are Muslim Roma.

00:29:58.630 --> 00:30:01.120
Henna is actually used by Eastern
Orthodox in Greece as well.

00:30:01.120 --> 00:30:05.510
It's a vegetable dye that
you put on the bride's hair.

00:30:05.510 --> 00:30:21.440
[ Music ]

