00:37:01.430 --> 00:37:02.730
You've seen a little bit

00:37:02.730 --> 00:37:04.520
about different kinds
of Romani communities.

00:37:04.520 --> 00:37:09.700
So only a few bands from
the Balkans have made it

00:37:09.700 --> 00:37:13.720
into you might say the world music
market, have been successful.

00:37:13.720 --> 00:37:15.660
But when non-Roma kind of see them,

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:19.640
they sort of think every Romani
orchestra back in the village is

00:37:19.640 --> 00:37:22.840
like benefitting from
a festival in Belgium.

00:37:22.840 --> 00:37:24.500
And that's really a
false impression.

00:37:24.500 --> 00:37:28.760
Only a few bands get hired over
and over again in the West.

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:33.750
So this Balkan Trafik Festival that
I mention, had three brass bands.

00:37:33.750 --> 00:37:38.140 position:56%
Two of them were from South Serbia,
this one, Boban and Marko Markovich,

00:37:38.140 --> 00:37:42.380
Ekrem Mamutovich from
like just 10 miles away.

00:37:42.380 --> 00:37:45.130
And why did they need
to have two bands?

00:37:45.130 --> 00:37:48.730
Because they staged a
Balkan brass battle.

00:37:48.730 --> 00:37:52.230
Again, the promotors
figure out gimmicks in order

00:37:52.230 --> 00:37:55.320 position:56%
to present these bands in a new way.

00:37:55.320 --> 00:37:57.040
So I'll get back to that later on.

00:37:57.040 --> 00:38:00.370
And a third band from
Macedonia, the Braka Kadrievi,

00:38:00.370 --> 00:38:03.190
half of whom actually
