00:38:03.190 --> 00:38:04.900
So it was cheap to hire them.

00:38:04.900 --> 00:38:07.980
Now brass music is part
of Balkan tradition,

00:38:07.980 --> 00:38:09.450
but only in certain places.

00:38:09.450 --> 00:38:13.490
So this is in Southern
Serbia in a Serbian wedding

00:38:13.490 --> 00:38:15.230
where Romani musicians played.

00:38:15.230 --> 00:38:19.780
So it is active, but it's
actually declining in some parts.

00:38:19.780 --> 00:38:22.410
But you wouldn't know that if
you looked at a Western festival

00:38:22.410 --> 00:38:24.220
where all you see is brass.

00:38:24.220 --> 00:38:28.790
And also in Eastern Macedonia
you do have brass bands.

00:38:28.790 --> 00:38:31.730 position:56%
But due to this man, Goran Bregovic,

00:38:31.730 --> 00:38:37.360
brass has become the defining
genre of quote "Gypsy music."

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:42.820 position:56%
And he's a non-Romani man from
Bosnia of mixed background, Serbian,

00:38:42.820 --> 00:38:47.700
who worked with the filmmaker Emir
Kusturica and wrote the film music.

00:38:47.700 --> 00:38:49.950
But actually took it
from Romani sources

00:38:49.950 --> 00:38:52.950
and put his name as
the copyright owner.

00:38:52.950 --> 00:38:58.930
So he is absolutely hated and
reviled as a thief by most Roma.

00:38:58.930 --> 00:39:01.360
They call him an appropriator
and a thief,

00:39:01.360 --> 00:39:04.430
and yet he got the top
billing in Belgium.

00:39:04.430 --> 00:39:07.690
And he makes more money
than any Romani band.

00:39:07.690 --> 00:39:11.180
His fees are now about
30,000 euros for his show.

00:39:11.180 --> 00:39:13.560
He doesn't like appear
just for a little while.

00:39:13.560 --> 00:39:15.680
He needs his whole show.

00:39:15.680 --> 00:39:19.790
And he appeared at a Guca Brass
Band Festival, which is a festival

00:39:19.790 --> 00:39:22.610
of competition of the
best brass bands, okay?

00:39:22.610 --> 00:39:25.870
So he's really loved by
non-Romani audiences,

00:39:25.870 --> 00:39:28.350
and they even mistake him as Roma.

00:39:28.350 --> 00:39:31.350
They call him the, you know,
Ambassador of Romani Music.

00:39:31.350 --> 00:39:32.650
But he's not.

00:39:32.650 --> 00:39:37.470
So I'm drawing attention to
what I'm calling the dialog

00:39:37.470 --> 00:39:42.580
between celebratory and anxious
narratives of world music

00:39:42.580 --> 00:39:44.960
that Steven Feld has written about.

00:39:44.960 --> 00:39:50.620
And celebratory narratives
tend to look at appropriation

00:39:50.620 --> 00:39:53.540 position:56%
and exchange as a win-win situation.

00:39:53.540 --> 00:39:58.670
All you're doing is providing new
creativity, new artistic impetus.

00:39:58.670 --> 00:40:00.080
What could be bad about it

00:40:00.080 --> 00:40:02.180
when we're all sharing
each other's culture?

00:40:02.180 --> 00:40:05.250
The anxious narratives
-- of course I'm going

00:40:05.250 --> 00:40:08.000
to critique the celebratory
-- but the anxious narratives,

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:09.920
I would critique some of them, too,

00:40:09.920 --> 00:40:11.640
because some of the
anxious narratives are

00:40:11.640 --> 00:40:13.200
about purity of music.

00:40:13.200 --> 00:40:15.030
We should keep things pure.

00:40:15.030 --> 00:40:16.760
And I don't subscribe
to that at all.

00:40:16.760 --> 00:40:18.420
Romani music has never been pure.

00:40:18.420 --> 00:40:24.070
Romani music has been an economic
commodity; has always been given

00:40:24.070 --> 00:40:27.560
and taken by neighboring peoples.

00:40:27.560 --> 00:40:31.560
But I do subscribe to the
anxious mentality when we talk

00:40:31.560 --> 00:40:33.260
about the political economy.

00:40:33.260 --> 00:40:38.090
What are the terms of the
trade when you exchange music?

00:40:38.090 --> 00:40:39.890
Who is profiting?

00:40:39.890 --> 00:40:44.610
Who is setting the terms of
those contract or no contracts?

00:40:44.610 --> 00:40:49.090
Who's in charge of getting the
gigs, of dividing the money?

00:40:49.090 --> 00:40:53.160
The other thing is that
"hybridity" has been used a lot

00:40:53.160 --> 00:40:57.280
to valorize any type
of cultural exchange,

00:40:57.280 --> 00:40:59.860 position:56%
that something mixed is always good.

00:40:59.860 --> 00:41:04.070
It destabilizes these
old kind of categories,

00:41:04.070 --> 00:41:07.600
the binaries that we
have, that mixtures

00:41:07.600 --> 00:41:09.840
and borders are inherently good.

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:15.090
But I would say that there's a
very healthy critique of hybridity.

00:41:15.090 --> 00:41:18.160
Hybridity is also a
marketing category.

00:41:18.160 --> 00:41:23.110
It's been used to actually put
a stamp on the earlier category

00:41:23.110 --> 00:41:26.340
that valorized ethnic
music as authentic.

00:41:26.340 --> 00:41:30.400
Like ethnic music comes from
kind of stable communities

00:41:30.400 --> 00:41:34.180
that have their real folklore,
their real traditions.

00:41:34.180 --> 00:41:37.080
That was the earlier phase
of world music marketing

00:41:37.080 --> 00:41:38.560
in like, you know, the '80s.

00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:42.280
But by the '90s, now you
see marketing that says

00:41:42.280 --> 00:41:44.960 position:56%
if it's hybrid it must be authentic.

00:41:44.960 --> 00:41:46.890
So they hybrid becomes
the authentic.

00:41:46.890 --> 00:41:51.020 position:56%
And I think we have to be suspicious
of all of these marketing labels,

00:41:51.020 --> 00:41:54.080
especially because hybridity
has actually been used

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:58.010
to discredit Gypsy music
in the scholarship.

00:41:58.010 --> 00:42:02.360
Serbian scholars have said they
don't play real Serbian music.

00:42:02.360 --> 00:42:06.910
They just play their version
with some kind of, you know,

00:42:06.910 --> 00:42:11.240
Eastern ornaments or some
corrupted type of rhythms.

00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:15.400
So, again, hybridity is
not inherently liberating

00:42:15.400 --> 00:42:17.140
or progressive.

00:42:17.140 --> 00:42:19.530
It has to be seen in its context.

00:42:19.530 --> 00:42:24.850
So I'm actually analyzing
how decisions get made

00:42:24.850 --> 00:42:29.290
about releasing Gypsy music
to non-Roma by looking

00:42:29.290 --> 00:42:30.770
at the producers themselves.

00:42:30.770 --> 00:42:35.280 position:56%
So one of the biggest production
houses is in Germany, Asphalt Tango,

00:42:35.280 --> 00:42:39.520
and they still do the old
types of stereotypes --

00:42:39.520 --> 00:42:42.730
exotic, sexual, passionate,
dangerous,

00:42:42.730 --> 00:42:45.620
from far away, maybe peasants.

00:42:45.620 --> 00:42:49.750
Again, either they are
authentic or hybrid as authentic.

00:42:49.750 --> 00:42:55.030
They picture Roma on their
CD covers as either villagers

00:42:55.030 --> 00:42:57.770
or living in mud or with animals.

00:42:57.770 --> 00:43:01.830
And they stage what I called
before the Balkan Brass Battle

00:43:01.830 --> 00:43:06.800
with two huge brass bands,
Boban Markovich from Serbia

00:43:06.800 --> 00:43:09.280
and Fanfare Ciocarlia as Romania.

00:43:09.280 --> 00:43:12.790
And the way they staged
it is to take this group,

00:43:12.790 --> 00:43:14.960
which does come a village,
from a village,

00:43:14.960 --> 00:43:16.260
so you could call them peasants.

00:43:16.260 --> 00:43:17.560
That's okay.

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:20.130
But they stage Boban
Markovich as cowboys.

00:43:20.130 --> 00:43:22.470
So it was the cowboys
versus the peasants.

00:43:22.470 --> 00:43:26.300
So they wore cowboy hats, and
this is how they were portrayed,

00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:29.880
and it was a kind of almost
violent type of thing on stage.

00:43:29.880 --> 00:43:33.750
In fact, one of the stagers
told me they were supposed

00:43:33.750 --> 00:43:38.340 position:56%
to take their trumpets, go back to
back, walk three paces, turn around,

00:43:38.340 --> 00:43:41.100
and then play at each
other like it's a duel.

00:43:41.100 --> 00:43:44.280
So, again, they're hinting
at kind of violence.

00:43:44.280 --> 00:43:46.570
&gt;&gt; Sani Rifati: They
got that from Americans?

00:43:46.570 --> 00:43:47.870
&gt;&gt; Carol Silverman: Yes.

00:43:47.870 --> 00:43:50.360
So these questions I've been
asking are about representation,

00:43:50.360 --> 00:43:54.670
about hybridity, about who
benefits from the popularization

00:43:54.670 --> 00:43:56.120
of Balkan Gypsy music

00:43:56.120 --> 00:43:59.800
and the economic context
in hierarchies of power.

