00:51:23.710 --> 00:51:31.470
&gt;&gt; Audience member: I'm
wondering if it's a question

00:51:31.470 --> 00:51:34.560
of the zurla [inaudible],
the Roma and the --

00:51:34.560 --> 00:51:37.660
&gt;&gt; Carol Silverman: So, the
zurla or zurna was banned

00:51:37.660 --> 00:51:41.490
in Bulgaria during the
Socialist period in 1984.

00:51:41.490 --> 00:51:45.530
So between '84 and '89 you
couldn't play that loud instrument.

00:51:45.530 --> 00:51:47.040
It's the first one you heard.

00:51:47.040 --> 00:51:49.740
That outdoor instrument
that's double-reeded.

00:51:49.740 --> 00:51:52.650
And that was a Socialist
Government decision --

00:51:52.650 --> 00:51:59.400
probably had input from
Moscow of targeting Muslims

00:51:59.400 --> 00:52:01.680
and Roma, so Turks and Roma.

00:52:01.680 --> 00:52:05.630
So the Romani language,
Turkish language, circumcisions,

00:52:05.630 --> 00:52:08.960
Romani costume, Turkish
costume, and zurla were outlawed.

00:52:08.960 --> 00:52:12.150
But after 1989 it's now free.

00:52:12.150 --> 00:52:15.390
So Roma are playing
the zurla everywhere.

00:52:15.390 --> 00:52:19.300
My point was that zurla is
not found in the festivals

00:52:19.300 --> 00:52:21.610
for non-Roma if you wondered that.

00:52:21.610 --> 00:52:22.910
Yeah.

00:52:22.910 --> 00:52:24.970
&gt;&gt; Sani Rifati: Carol,
under the Communism,

00:52:24.970 --> 00:52:29.330
most of these Eastern European
countries would really sponsor

00:52:29.330 --> 00:52:34.620
and finance their national
instrument from the country.

00:52:34.620 --> 00:52:40.990
Given that zurla comes from India,
it was foreign to Bavarians.

00:52:40.990 --> 00:52:42.970
But in the meantime compared

00:52:42.970 --> 00:52:46.310
to [inaudible] these instruments
were the Romance diaspora,

00:52:46.310 --> 00:52:51.490
not the ethnic Bavarians or
other groups in the Balkans.

00:52:51.490 --> 00:52:56.100
So many instruments were their
music preserved no matter what.

00:52:56.100 --> 00:52:57.790
Even [inaudible].

00:52:57.790 --> 00:52:59.090
&gt;&gt; Carol Silverman: Yeah.

00:52:59.090 --> 00:53:02.250
Zurla players, even when it was
illegal and you could go to jail

00:53:02.250 --> 00:53:05.960
for playing it, were playing
it in private ceremonies

00:53:05.960 --> 00:53:10.440
with somebody posted on the roof
to look out for police coming.

00:53:10.440 --> 00:53:12.680
Okay? So if you make
something illegal,

00:53:12.680 --> 00:53:14.900
that doesn't necessarily
mean it goes away.

00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:17.580
It goes underground, and
actually becomes more important

00:53:17.580 --> 00:53:19.510
to people's life.

00:53:19.510 --> 00:53:22.950
Bulgarian wedding music
was also prohibited,

00:53:22.950 --> 00:53:24.250
and people went to jail for it.

00:53:24.250 --> 00:53:26.840
And that survived underground
as well.

00:53:26.840 --> 00:53:28.140
Yes.

